      <details>
        <summary>Is the hacking in the Tracker TV show realistic?</summary>
        <p>Like most Hollywood productions, the hacking in Tracker is highly dramatized for pacing. Real-world hacking rarely involves flying 3D graphics or instantaneous access. However, the core concepts—such as exploiting open-source intelligence (OSINT), social engineering, and misconfigured APIs—are grounded in genuine cybersecurity principles.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does geolocation tracking work in real life compared to the show?</summary>
        <p>In the show, tracking a phone seems instantaneous and precise to the millimeter. In reality, cell tower triangulation provides a wide radius (often miles), while GPS requires the device to be active and transmitting data. Law enforcement or sophisticated actors use 'Stingrays' (IMSI catchers) or demand data from carriers, a process that usually takes hours or days, not seconds.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What tech stack would you use to build a system like the one in Tracker?</summary>
