      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can anyone access the databases shown in the Tracker TV show?</summary>
        <p>The highly centralized 'god-mode' databases shown on TV don't exist in a single accessible form. Instead, data is fractured across hundreds of commercial data brokers (like LexisNexis or Experian), public government records, and social media platforms. Accessing this requires paying for API access to these brokers, not just 'hacking into the mainframe.'</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why do TV shows misrepresent software engineering?</summary>
        <p>Software engineering is inherently non-visual and time-consuming. Watching a developer spend four hours debugging a CORS error or writing a SQL query doesn't make for compelling television. Shows compress timelines and create visual abstractions to keep the narrative moving and maintain tension.</p>
      </details>
